snippet.textDisplay:
I have not seen IX.
To my knowledge, in the film, Palpatine says Rey is his granddaughter.
Was is said that Palpatine had another son or daughter that would have been Reys parents?
As far as I know, no.
I am drawing my theory on the idea that Palpatine is the "father" of Anakin, who was conceived by the force to Shmi Skywalker. Anakin(Palpatine/Skywalker) had two children--Luke & Leia. They are Palpatines "grandchildren".
I have strong belief that Rey is the product of cloning. Cloning is big in Star wars, the entire storm trooper army, Boba Fett, Snoke, and even The Mandolorian's Baby Yoda--but that is another can of worms.
Rey does not have "Parents" but was engineered from the DNA found in the hand of Luke Skywalker that was cut from him by Vader in ESB when he lost his Fathers lightsaber. There are hints and reasons to make this theory valid. The lightsaber was recovered and given to Rey, There was so much attention given to the fact that Luke's hand was cut off, but no explanation as to why or what the point of it was. This theory gives a lot of validation to it happening.
So, from a "certain point of view" Rey is the grandchild of Palpatine. Rey does not have "parents". Rey can choose to adopt the name Skywalker as both Anakin and Luke had.
Thoughts?

snippet.textDisplay: I mean pacing was all over the place and callbacks were beyond rapid fire, but all and all I love this movie.  Given how divided the reaction to TLJ was this was equal parts course correction and continuing with threads set up.  I think what made people angry was that it took "less chances" despite being the Skywalker/Palpatine Saga's definitive end.  It had no choice but to use callbacks, from the 3o, 2p, 1s callback of a Skywalker on Tatooine to the 3p, 2o, 1s of the Emperor's reappearance.  It really was the endpoint of not just the sequels but of the original and prequel trilogies.  I am however weirded out by folk that wanted C3P0, Chewie and the Falcon to die or stay dead saying that was taking chances.
